1. Explain Switch 

ANS-A network switch is a device that connects devices within a network, forwarding data packets based on MAC addresses.
 It operates at the data link layer (Layer 2), enabling efficient communication between devices in the same VLAN.
 Switches enhance network performance by reducing collisions and segmenting traffic.

2. Explain Switch Boot Sequence 

ANS-A Cisco switch boot sequence starts with the Power-On Self-Test (POST) to check hardware.
 The bootstrap loads the Cisco IOS from flash memory. The IOS initializes, loads the configuration from NVRAM, 
And starts interfaces.
 The switch then runs Spanning Tree Protocol and is ready for operation.


3. Explain Three Methods to access Switch Command Line 
Interface 

ANS-Three methods to access a Cisco switchâ€™s Command Line Interface (CLI) are:

 (a)Console: Connect via a console port using a rollover cable and terminal emulator (e.g., PuTTY) for direct access.
 (b)Telnet: Remotely access the CLI over the network using Telnet, requiring VTY configuration and an IP address.
 (c)SSH: Securely access the CLI remotely via SSH, needing VTY setup, IP, and crypto key generation.


